ðŸ“– **Description:**
    The `infotocap` command reads `terminfo` files and prints the information in `termcap` format. `Terminfo` is a newer terminal database format, while `termcap` is older and still used by some applications. Essentially, `infotocap` converts `terminfo` to `termcap`.

âš™ï¸ **Options:**
    ðŸ”¹ `infotocap` --> Uses the default `terminfo` file (usually `/usr/share/terminfo`).
    ðŸ”¹ `infotocap -v` --> Shows the program version.
    ðŸ”¹ `infotocap -d` --> Don't use the default `terminfo` directory; use `$TERMINFO` instead. If `$TERMINFO` is not set, use `/usr/lib/terminfo`.

ðŸ›  **Examples:**

    $ infotocap screen.xterm

    ðŸ”¹ Reads the `terminfo` entry for `screen.xterm` from the default database and prints the equivalent `termcap` code.

    $ infotocap -d ./myterm mytermname

    ðŸ”¹ Reads the `terminfo` entry for `mytermname` from the directory `./myterm` and prints the `termcap` code.

âœ… **Simple Example:**

    $ infotocap xterm-256color | head -n 5

    ðŸ”¹ Finds the `terminfo` entry for `xterm-256color`, converts it to `termcap`, and prints the first 5 lines of the output.  This is useful to quickly verify that the conversion works as expected without viewing the entire output.
